Data

Our data come in the form of Zagat reviews from 168 Italian restaurants in New York City from 2001. The Zagat guide is an influential review of restaurants. They are made famous by their use of selective quotes from actual diners to build a pithy description of each restaurant. But we wont be working with the text. Rather, we will be working with the numeric reviews. Each restaurant is rated on a scale of 0 to 30 for the quality of its food, decor, and service. The average price of a mealwhich includes one drink and a tip will be our response variable.

Go ahead and copy the data file nyc.csv from the COURSE_MATERIALS/LABS folder into the same directory as your lab report.

Then type the following code in the setup code chunk of your document to read the dataset into a data frame called nyc_italian. Dont forget to run the code to load the dataframe in your working Environment.

nyc_italian <- read_csv(file = "nyc.csv")

Creating the Training/Testing Split

Before we begin building models, let us first randomly split the dataset into two subsets:

  • the training split will contain 80% of the data and we will use this for building our model.

  • the testing split will contain the remaining 20% and we will use this for comparing the models we build on their predictive abilities.

Create a new code chunk called data-splitting with chunk option set to include = FALSE and type the following in it. See the footnote1 for an explanation of this chunk option. Go ahead and run the code chunk as well so you can view the data subsets in your spreadsheet viewer.

set.seed(1414)          #set random number seed

nyc_split <- initial_split(nyc_italian, prop = 0.8) #split data in two

nyc_train <- training(nyc_split) #training subset
nyc_test <- testing(nyc_split)   #testing subset

As an example, the code below illustrates how you might fit modelx relating a response \(y\) to an explanatory variable \(x\), and save the numeric value of the adjusted \(R^2\) from that model in a variable called modelx.rsq.

modelx <- lm(y ~ x, data = <dataset name>)

modelx.rsq <- glance(modelx) %>% 
                    select(adj.r.squared) %>% pull()

We will now consider adding the categorical variable east as a predictor to our simple linear model. There are two ways to accomplish this, one is via a main effects model in which the influence of the explanatory variable on the response is unaffected by the other variables in the model. The other is an interaction effects model in which the influence of an explanatory variable on the response depends on the other variables in the model.

Model validation

Now that we have a few models under our belt, we will proceed to see how well they predict the Price for the restaurants in the testing dataset.

Recall that in order to examine how well a model predicts outcomes on the testing data, we can use the augment function from the tidymodels package. This function takes the output from lm and calculates predictions using the fitted model for a new dataset. It augments the dataset by adding two new columns called .fitted and .resid which contain the predicted value and prediction error for each observation.

As an example, the code below illustrates how you might use the modelx relating a response \(y\) to an explanatory variable \(x\), which was trained on dataset 1 to predict outcomes for testing dataset 2. We then calculate the accuracy of these predictions by calculating the Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) which is the average difference between the predictions and the actual observed values (on a squared scale). The smaller the RMSE, the better the model is at predicting new outcomes.

Once again, the numeric value of the RMSE for a model can be saved as a numeric variable and included within text or in the cell of a table using inline code.

#fit modelx on dataset 1 and save result to R object modelx

modelx <- lm(y ~ x, data = <dataset 1>)

#augment dataset 2 with predicted values and prediction 
#errors using modelx and save augmented dataframe

modelx_pred <- augment(modelx, newdata  = <dataset 2> ) 

#calculate the RMSE of the predictions

modelx.rmse <- modelx_pred %>% 
                 rmse(truth = y, estimate = .fitted) %>% pull()

The RMSE is not a percentage and you can just report it to 2 decimal places. For example, you may have output like the following.

Model Root mean square error (RMSE)
model0 5.08
